<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex</i> <i>lentiformis</i> or <i>Atriplex</i> <i>torreyi</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>canescens</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>pilularis</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>salicifolia</i>, <i>Distichlis</i> <i>spicata</i>, <i>Encelia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Kochia</i> <i>americana</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Pluchea</i> <i>sericea</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>integrifolia</i>, <i>Sporobolus</i> <i>airoides</i>, <i>Suaeda</i> <i>taxifolia</i> and <i>Tamarix</i> spp. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Myoporum</i> <i>laetum</i> or <i>Prosopis</i> <i>glandulosa</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 5 m, canopy is open to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is variable. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Atriplex lentiformis</i> is > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b, Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006).</li>
		
		<li><i>Atriplex lentiformis</i> or <i>Atriplex torreyi</i> is > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (VegCAMP and AIS 2013).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Gentle to steep southeast- and southwest-facing slopes. Soils are clays. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Atriplex lentiformis</i> as a FAC plant. </div>
</div>

        
