<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Data are incomplete on the response of <i>Atriplex lentiformis </i>to fire. <i>A. lentiformis </i>can survive some fires, and the most likely post-fire regeneration strategy is seed production. No reports exist showing sprouting or adventitious buds. <i>A. lentiformis </i>is likely to have the best chance to persist when fire severity and frequency are low. Also, <i>A. lentiformis </i>has been shown to have high moisture content, and its flammability is reduced when plant moisture is high (Meyer 2005a). The species has been studied as a fire retardant species because of its naturally high moisture content, and it is expected to produce less of a fire hazard in southern California than chaparral stands in the dry season (Montgomery and Cheo 1969). Processes other than fire tend to affect its occurrence. These are primarily related to fluvial disturbance and shifts in groundwater availability.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Long (35-100 years)
				
