</div>



    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Atriplex lentiformis</i> includes the Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261F) and Sonoran Desert (322B) sections.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa). Stands have been observed along Carquinez Straight near Martinez.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ai-j). Stands are likely to occur in some of the inland valleys such as the Carrizo Plain.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-c). Wash stands are recognized in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park in the Dubber Springs-Jacumba Valley area, often containing <i>Sporobolus airoides</i> (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b). Stands also occur in the Coachella Valley with <i>A. canescens</i> present (Pearcy and Harrison 1974).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Al, Aq, Av-y). Stands have been planted and exist naturally in Suisun Marsh along borders of managed fields and intermittently flooded wetlands, where around 12 ha were mapped (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000). Stands are associated with alkali wetlands in much of the western San Joaquin Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ag). Stands occur around springs and alkali seeps and in alkali meadows, including areas with past disturbance. Two vegetation types of <i>Atriplex torreyi</i> are reported from the Owens Valley on alkaline soils that have sparse and high cover of meadow associates (Manning 1994). Stands also are reported from Edwards Air Force Base (Charlton 2000a), which often contain <i>Prosopis glandulosa.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Di). Stands are expected from Chalfont Valley near Benton.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bd-g, Bj). Stands exist on roadsides in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), including on sandy flats adjacent to Point Mugu Lagoon (Pearcy and Harrison 1974). Many of the roadside stands are likely from CalTrans plantings and other restoration efforts, although natural populations do occur in this section. No attempt was made to differentiate associations in the Santa Monica Mountains because they may be introduced, and the stands are heterogeneous. The extensive list of non-native species associated with these stands may be another indication of their nonnatural origins. Similar stands also have been observed at Cabrillo National Monument on Point Loma.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bj, Bl, Bp). Stands are described for some springs and seeps on the western side of Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b). Stands also are likely to occur in the inland portions of western Riverside Co.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands have been planted in various saline and alkaline wetlands to increase scrub cover for wildlife (e.g., in Suisun Marsh). <i>Atriplex lentiformis </i>has been used for erosion control on disturbed riparian sites in the San Joaquin Valley and near Tapo Canyon Creek, California (Favorite 2005a). </div>
</div>

    

    

